<br>
The non-RP, casual RP, and agnostic RP players who have intoned into this, and any other RP/PG flame, have always said they feel free to RP without anyone mocking them. It is only the hardline RPer who have come up with the scenerios where RP is not allowed or mocked. These are just scenerios, no real life (in game of course) situations have been reported. I refuse to accept these diatribes into speculation until actula damages are done. Potential issues are just your own opinions.<br>
<br>
Someone in this thread told us they always try to read the best possible intentions into the text. This is a great concept, so let's extend that same courtesy to players in the game. Do not assume that they came here just to ruin your own RP world that you have created here. You can each create your own world and control it completely, as long as you do not let other peoples actions to affect you. Just like RL, you chose your attitude and response.<br>
<br>
This is a RP preferred server. The special rules, however, are enforced for all. We are a community here, bound by the special rules and our own decision to come here for them. Please do not segregate us into RP, PG and the unwashed masses. Let's live and let live and assume people will allow each other to have their own brand of enjoyment in the game.<br>
<br>
I enjoy the debate engendered by the RP and PG threads. It is a great way to get through the day at work. When I log onto EG, however, I would like to pretend these threads do not exist and enjoy my leisure. I trust you all feel the same<br>
<br>
<br>
Borm. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubormwarrior.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Borm Warrior</A> at: 2/5/02 4:45:24 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/unimiane.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nimiane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 19<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/5/02 7:06:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=317.topic&index=53>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Exactly!</span><hr size=1> Amen, Borm!<br>
<br>
I really don't want to get into Semantic Wars: Eposide 200023409825 over what words triggered what response, and how I could have read any number of the things that I did into the original post.  I do have one minor question, though, if it is not powergamers (ie. non-roleplayers) that we are talking about in this thread, then who or what are we talking about?  The whole idea of &quot;safe space&quot; or &quot;viable haven&quot; implies keeping safe from *something*.. doesn't it?   <br>
<br>
At any rate, I am completely in agreement with Borm.  I just want to log in, make some friends, have some fun roleplaying and relax.  I will do my small part to keep roleplay &quot;viable&quot; by attempting to keep a sense of character while I'm there, and not judge others on the extent to which they choose to develop, or not develop, their characters. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uqixxfv.showPublicProfile?language=EN>QixxFV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Thats not my tail</span><br>  Posts: 75<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/6/02 6:14:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=317.topic&index=54>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Exactly!</span><hr size=1> i would just like to add that this is genious.<br>
<br>
&quot;you are totally right that the vast majority of us out there read things in a negative light first. That's the bad thing about virtual communication, it seems to be 25% the words on the page and 75% in the mind of the person reading it - their perception of you from past interaction, the mood that they are in, the emotional response they get to words that you use, their perception of your tone, right or wrong. Your writing skill can change those percentages one way or the other .. but overall it's still an imprecise science at best&quot;<br>
